SIMPLE: scud
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scud
<hw>Scud</hw> <pr>(sk⟦ucr⟧d)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Scudded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Scudding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Dan. <ets>skyde</ets> to shoot,
shove, push, akin to <ets>skud</ets> shot, gunshot, a shoot, young
bough, and to E. <ets>shoot</ets>. ⟦root⟧159. See <er>Shoot</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To move swiftly; especially, to move as if driven
forward by something.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The first nautilus that <qex>scudded</qex> upon the glassy surface
of warm primeval oceans.</q> <rj><qau>I. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The wind was high; the vast white clouds <qex>scudded</qex> over
the blue heaven.</q> <rj><qau>Beaconsfield.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To be driven swiftly, or to run,
before a gale, with little or no sail spread.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scud</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Scud
<hw>Scud</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To pass over quickly.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Shenstone.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scud</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Scud
<hw>Scud</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of scudding; a
driving along; a rushing with precipitation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Loose, vapory clouds driven swiftly by the
wind.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Borne on the <qex>scud</qex> of the sea.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>scud</qex> was flying fast above us, throwing a veil over
the moon.</q> <rj><qau>Sir S. Baker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A slight, sudden shower.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Wright.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A small flight of larks, or other
birds, less than a flock.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any swimming amphipod
crustacean.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Storm scud</b></col>. <cd>See the Note under
<er>Cloud</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scuddle</ent>⟦br⟧
